    "ကျွန်မ ကလေး မှန်ကြည်ဆေး တွေ သောက် ပစ် လိုက် လို့ ပါ ။": 261,


==========

All three models predict the same wrong label and thus, modeling is working. However, the predicted labels are wrong. Why?

## Debugging

Found it. The entire training used **consistently wrong video↔annotation pairs** due to alphabetical string sorting. `sorted()` puts `idx20-100.mp4` before `idx20-31.mp4` (because `"1" < "3"` as strings), so every video was matched to the wrong annotation. Training achieved 100% because the same wrong mapping was applied consistently to both train and test — but at inference time the user knows the real label. Everything must be re-run after fixing the sort.Confirmed. Now fix `match_videos_to_annotations` in `utils.py` to use numeric natural sort:Now add the `re` import (it's not in the current imports):Good, `re` is already imported. Now also fix `extract_all_videos` in `extract_keypoints.py` — it has the same bug:Now verify the fix is correct with a simulation of your actual filenames:Confirmed. `idx20-31.mp4` was at position 234 (wrong) and is now at position 30 (correct) = annotation 30 = "ချိုင့် ။". Copy both fixed files:Replace both files and re-run the **entire pipeline from scratch**:

```bash
cp utils.py           /mnt/disk1/ye/exp/msl_recognition/src/utils.py
cp extract_keypoints.py /mnt/disk1/ye/exp/msl_recognition/src/extract_keypoints.py

# Must redo everything — keypoints, augmentation, training, evaluation
cd /mnt/disk1/ye/exp/msl_recognition

# Step 1: keypoints already exist but were extracted correctly
#         (extraction order doesn't affect .npy content — each video
#          is processed independently, so keypoints are still valid)
#         NO need to re-extract!

# Step 2: Re-run data prep to rebuild correct video→annotation mapping
time bash scripts/01_prepare_data.sh

# Step 3: Delete old augmented data (wrong labels) and regenerate
rm -rf data/augmented/
time bash scripts/03_augment_data.sh

# Step 4: Delete old results and retrain everything
rm -rf results/exp_bilstm results/exp_transformer results/exp_stgcn
rm -rf results/cv_bilstm results/cv_transformer results/cv_stgcn

time bash scripts/04_train.sh bilstm      exp_bilstm
time bash scripts/05_evaluate.sh bilstm   exp_bilstm

time bash scripts/04_train.sh transformer exp_transformer
time bash scripts/05_evaluate.sh transformer exp_transformer

time bash scripts/04_train.sh stgcn       exp_stgcn
time bash scripts/05_evaluate.sh stgcn    exp_stgcn
```

---

**Root cause — one line, massive impact:**

```python
# BEFORE (wrong): alphabetical string sort
all_videos = sorted([p for p in video_dir.rglob('*') ...])
#   idx20-1 → idx20-10 → idx20-100 → idx20-101 → ... → idx20-31 → ...
#   idx20-31.mp4 was at position 234, matched to annotation 234

# AFTER (correct): numeric natural sort
all_videos = sorted([...], key=_numeric_sort_key)
#   idx20-1 → idx20-2 → ... → idx20-30 → idx20-31 → ...
#   idx20-31.mp4 is at position 30, correctly matched to annotation 30 = "ချိုင့် ။"
```

**Why training "succeeded" at 100% with wrong labels:** The same wrong sort was applied consistently in both `match_videos_to_annotations` (for label assignment) and in `augment_dataset_all_classes` (which uses those matched records). So the model learned `video_31_keypoints → class_234` and the test set also had `video_31_keypoints → class_234`. It got 100% because the labels were wrong in the same systematic way throughout. But at inference time, you know the real label — so the model appeared wrong.

**The keypoints themselves are still valid** — each `.npy` file was extracted from its own video correctly. Only the `video → annotation` mapping was scrambled. Re-running from `01_prepare_data.sh` rebuilds that mapping correctly.


